  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It is universally recognized as a criminal activity because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities without detection and reinvest those profits into further illegal ventures or legitimate businesses, thereby undermining the integrity of financial systems.\n\nVirtually all countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often in alignment with international standards set by organizations such as:\n\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: An intergovernmental body that sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures.\n2. **United Nations (UN)**: Through conventions like the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime and the UN Convention against Corruption.\n3. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**: These organizations assist countries in implementing AML/CFT frameworks.\n\nPenalties for money laundering vary by jurisdiction but typically include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Financial institutions and businesses are also required to implement robust compliance programs to detect and report suspicious activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is unequivocally illegal worldwide, and there is broad international agreement on the need to combat it through legislation, enforcement, and cooperation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
